==Abstract==

This IIP specifies using Median Time-Past (MTP) of the previous 11 blocks as the reference point for lock-time calculations, instead of block timestamp.

==Motivation==

Using MTP instead of block timestamp provides:
* Miner manipulation resistance (single miners cannot advance time significantly)
* Predictability (MTP increases monotonically)
* Consensus stability (reduces timestamp-based attack vectors)

==Specification==

===Median Time-Past Calculation===

<pre>
int64_t GetMedianTimePast(const CBlockIndex* pindex) {
    int64_t timestamps[11];
    const CBlockIndex* p = pindex;

    for (int i = 0; i < 11 && p; i++) {
        timestamps[i] = p->GetBlockTime();
        p = p->pprev;
    }

    std::sort(timestamps, timestamps + 11);
    return timestamps[5];  // Median of 11 values
}
</pre>

===Lock-Time Validation===

For transactions with time-based nLockTime (>= 500,000,000):

<pre>
// IIP-41: Use MTP for locktime validation
if (nLockTime >= 500000000 && nLockTime > GetMedianTimePast(pindexPrev))
    return false;  // Not yet valid
</pre>

===Affected Operations===

{| class="wikitable"
|-
! Operation !! Reference Time
|-
| nLockTime validation || MTP of previous block
|-
| OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY (IIP-6) || MTP of previous block
|-
| Relative time-locks (IIP-7) || MTP at output confirmation
|}

===Why 11 Blocks?===

* 6 confirmations of honest timestamps needed to manipulate
* ~11 minutes of history at 1-minute blocks
* Balance between stability and responsiveness

===Monotonicity===

MTP is guaranteed to never decrease, even if individual block timestamps vary. This ensures lock-times behave predictably.

==Security Considerations==

===Time-Warp Attack Mitigation===

MTP limits the impact of timestamp manipulation:
* A majority of miners would need to collude
* Even then, time can only advance by ~1 hour over 6 blocks
* Network would notice obvious manipulation

===Future Timestamp Limit===

Blocks are still subject to the 2-hour future timestamp limit, independent of MTP.

